# Coverage Guidance

## Configuration

- Keep coverage config in `.coveragerc` or `[tool.coverage]` in
  `pyproject.toml`; avoid splitting run and report settings across files.
- Set `source` to the project package so installed dependencies and tests do
  not inflate results.
- Use `omit` for generated files, migrations, or platform-specific glue that
  the project intentionally excludes.
- Enable `branch = true`; line coverage alone misses untaken branches.

## Branch Coverage

- Branch coverage is almost always the right default because conditionals,
  early returns, and exception paths are where regressions hide.
- Review missing branches before raising thresholds; a high line percentage can
  still leave failure paths unexecuted.
- Keep pragmas such as `# pragma: no cover` rare and explain them when the
  reason is not obvious.

## Thresholds In CI

- Use `fail_under = 80` or the project's configured threshold so regressions
  fail consistently.
- Prefer `coverage report --fail-under=80` in CI when the threshold is managed
  by the workflow.
- Enforce the same threshold locally and in CI; CI-only thresholds create
  avoidable friction during pull requests.
- Keep threshold changes separate from large test rewrites so reviewers can see
  whether coverage actually improved.

## HTML Reports

- Use `coverage html` for local inspection of missed lines and branches.
- Keep `htmlcov/`, `.coverage`, and parallel coverage data files out of source
  control.
- Link or upload HTML reports only when CI consumers need them.

## Avoid

- Measuring coverage without branch coverage enabled.
- Committing `htmlcov/` or `.coverage` to the repository.
- Treating 100% coverage as the goal; coverage measures execution, not
  correctness.
- Omitting `__init__.py` files from source coverage.
